&lt;/h1>&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>&lt;strong>TL;DR&lt;/strong>&lt;br>
&lt;code>SIGKILL&lt;/code> and &lt;code>SIGSTOP&lt;/code> are meant to be final, but three kernel pathways let a task survive:&lt;/p>
&lt;ol>
&lt;li>The processâ€™s &lt;code>SIGNAL_UNKILLABLE&lt;/code> flag is set (PIDÂ 1 has this by default).&lt;/li>
&lt;li>The thread is stuck in an uninterruptible sleep (&lt;code>D&lt;/code> state) while inside the kernel.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>A tracer, cgroup freezer, or rogue kernel module silently drops or delays the signal.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;p>Below weâ€™ll &lt;strong>reproduce the first case&lt;/strong> with a 25â€‘line kernel module driven by Python, then learn to spot the other two cases with pure Python.&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;hr>
&lt;h2 id="1why-sigkill-ought-to-win">&lt;a href="#1why-sigkill-ought-to-win" class="header-anchor">&lt;/a>1Â Â Why &lt;code>SIGKILL&lt;/code> &lt;em>ought&lt;/em> to win
&lt;/h2>&lt;ul>
&lt;li>In the LinuxÂ &lt;code>signal(7)&lt;/code> manual, &lt;strong>&lt;code>SIGKILLÂ (9)&lt;/code>&lt;/strong> and &lt;strong>&lt;code>SIGSTOPÂ (19)&lt;/code>&lt;/strong> are marked â€œcannot be caught, blocked, or ignored.â€&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Delivery can fail only when
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>the caller lacks permission (&lt;code>kill()&lt;/code> returnsÂ &lt;code>EPERM&lt;/code>), &lt;strong>or&lt;/strong>&lt;/li>
&lt;li>the targetâ€™s &lt;code>signal_structâ†’flags&lt;/code> carries the bit &lt;strong>&lt;code>SIGNAL_UNKILLABLE&lt;/code>&lt;/strong>.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>The kernel grants that flag to the very first userspace task (PIDÂ 1) so the system canâ€™t kill its own &lt;em>init&lt;/em>.&lt;/p>
&lt;hr>
&lt;h2 id="2flipping-signal_unkillable-build-an-immortal-process">&lt;a href="#2flipping-signal_unkillable-build-an-immortal-process" class="header-anchor">&lt;/a>2Â Â Flipping &lt;code>SIGNAL_UNKILLABLE&lt;/code>: build an â€œimmortalâ€ process
&lt;/h2>&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>âš ï¸Â &lt;strong>Run in a throwâ€‘away VM or container.&lt;/strong>&lt;br>
Once a PID is flagged unkillable, only a reboot or voluntary exit clears it.&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
